// Where are queues useful?

1. Keybord Buffer (letters should appear on the screen in the order theyre pressed)
2. printer Queue (Print jobs should be completed in the order)
3. Used in LinkedList, PriorityQueues, Breadth-first search;

in conclusion a queue is FIFO first-in first-out 

                   II./ Priority Queue
What the diiferent between the Priority Queue and Normal Queue?

// NORMAL QUEUE
// Queue = FIFO (First In First Out)
//  - Elements are served in the order they are added
//  - Example: People lining up at a cashier
//  - Operations:
//      enqueue (add to rear)
//      dequeue (remove from front)
//  - Peek = see the front element without removing
//  - Use cases:
//      - Printer queue
//      - BFS in graphs
//      - Task scheduling (simple order)


// PRIORITY QUEUE
// PriorityQueue = elements with HIGH priority served first
//  - Not strictly FIFO, priority decides order
//  - Example: Emergency room, critical patients treated first
//  - Operations:
//      add / offer (add element, automatically placed based on priority)
//      poll / remove (removes highest priority element)
//      peek (see element with highest priority without removing)
//  - If two elements have same priority, served in order they were added
//  - Use cases:
//      - Task scheduling in OS
//      - AI job queues
//      - Real-time systems where some tasks are more important

why the output of this code : 
code : 


import java.util.PriorityQueue;
import java.util.Queue;

public class PriorityQ{
    public static void main(String[] args)
    {
        Queue<String> queue = new PriorityQueue<>();
        queue.offer("b");
        queue.offer("c");
        queue.offer("a");
        queue.offer("d");

        while(!queue.isEmpty()){
            System.out.println(queue.peek());
            System.out.println(queue);
            System.out.println(queue.poll());
            
        }                      
    }
}
output :
a
[a, c, b, d]
a
b
[b, c, d]
b
c
[c, d]
c
d
[d]
d

why : a
[a, c, b, d]

 |
 v

Important rule:

PriorityQueue does NOT store elements as a fully sorted list.
It stores them as a HEAP.

A heap only guarantees that the first element is the smallest, not that the whole list is sorted.

So internally it may look like:

        a
       / \
      c   b
     /
    d


                            III. LinkedList
1.single LinkedList

A Linked List is a way to store data in memeory using nodes
that are connected with pointer (links) instead of storing
them next to each other like arry ,

structure
         | next is a node or pointer a reference to next node in list
         |
  | the value store
  V      V
[data | next ] -> [data | next ] -> [data | next ] -> null

example 

10 -> 20 -> 30 -> 40 -> null

Node
 ├── data
 └── next (pointer to next node)
   
2.Doubly LinkedList

A Doubly Linked List is an improved version of a linked list.
still like LinkedList it have data and node but this time structure like this

null <- [data | prev | next] <-> [data | prev | next] <-> [data | prev | next] -> null

example:  10 <-> 20 <-> 30 <-> 40

Node
 ├── prev
 ├── data
 └── next

 we can use Linked List with stack and Queue and The outcome
 are depend on what ur using like if ur using stack for example :

