                         BIG O notation
                     "How code slow as data grow"
1. describes the performace of algorithms as the amount of data 
increases 
2. Machine independent (# of step to completion )
3.ignore smaller operaion O(n + 1) -> O(n)

example :                       n = amount of data that we added up  
O(1) constant ttime                (its a variable like x)
O(n) linear time
O(log n) 
O(n^2)
O(n!)

O(1) = constant time 
      - random access of an element in an array
      - inserting at the begining of LinkedList
      - the fastest of the big O brothers

O(Log n ) = Logarithimc time 
           - binary search
           - second fastest after constant time

O(n) = Linear time 
     - looping through elements in an array
     - searching throught a Linkedlist
     - third fastest of the big O bro

O(n log n) = quasilinear time 
     - quiksort
     - mergesort
     - heapsort 

O(n^2) = quadratic time 
     - insearttion sort
     - selection sort 
     - bubble sort

O(n!) = factorial time 
     - travaling Salesman Problem
     - the slowest if the big O bros


     1. Linear search
    
// linear search = Ilterate through a collection
        // one element at a time
        // runtime complexity O(n)
        // Disadvantages:
        // slow for large data sets
        // Advantages:
        // fast for search of small to midium data sets
        // does not need to sorted 
        // useful for data structures that do not allow random access (linked list, etc)

        *note 
        for(int i = 0; i < array.length; i++){
            if(array[i] == value){
                return i;
            }
        }

        return -1; 
